.SH "NAME"
pam_rootok \- Gain only root access
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.HP \w'\fBpam_rootok\&.so\fR\ 'u
\fBpam_rootok\&.so\fR [debug]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
pam_rootok be a PAM module dat authenticates tha user if their
\fIUID\fR
is
\fI0\fR\& fo' realz. Applications dat is pimped setuid\-root generally retain the
\fIUID\fR
of tha user but run wit tha authoritizzle of a enhanced effective\-UID\&. Well shiiiit, it is tha real
\fIUID\fR
that is checked\&.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.PP
\fBdebug\fR
.RS 4
Print debug shiznit\&.
.RE
.SH "MODULE TYPES PROVIDED"
.PP
The
\fBauth\fR,
\fBacct\fR
and
\fBpassword\fR
module types is provided\&.
.SH "RETURN VALUES"
.PP
PAM_SUCCESS
.RS 4
The
\fIUID\fR
is
\fI0\fR\&.
.RE
.PP
PAM_AUTH_ERR
.RS 4
The
\fIUID\fR
is
\fBnot\fR\fI0\fR\&.
.RE
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
In tha case of the
\fBsu\fR(1)
application tha oldschool usage is ta permit tha superuser ta adopt tha identitizzle of a lesser user without tha use of a password\&. To obtain dis behavior wit PAM tha followin pair of lines is needed fo' tha correspondin entry up in the
/etc/pam\&.d/su
configuration file:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
# su authentication\&. Root is granted access by default\&.
auth  sufficient   pam_rootok\&.so
auth  required     pam_unix\&.so
      
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
